04619nam a22009855i 9780520944442DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20092009cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020758756  a97805209444427 a10.1525/97805209444422doi  a(DE-B1597)520629  a(OCoLC)1110719741  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aDG445 4aDG445b.S64 2009 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a302.209409032231 aSnyder, Jon R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDissimulation and the Culture of Secrecy in Early Modern Europe /cJon R. Snyder. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"Larvatus prodeo," announced René Descartes at the beginning of the seventeenth century: "I come forward, masked." Deliberately disguising or silencing their most intimate thoughts and emotions, many early modern Europeans besides Descartes-princes, courtiers, aristocrats and commoners alike-chose to practice the shadowy art of dissimulation. For men and women who could not risk revealing their inner lives to those around them, this art of incommunicativity was crucial, both personally and politically. Many writers and intellectuals sought to explain, expose, justify, or condemn the emergence of this new culture of secrecy, and from Naples to the Netherlands controversy swirled for two centuries around the powers and limits of dissimulation, whether in affairs of state or affairs of the heart. This beautifully written work crisscrosses Europe, with a special focus on Italy, to explore attitudes toward the art of dissimulation in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries. Discussing many canonical and lesser-known works, Jon R. Snyder examines the treatment of dissimulation in early modern treatises and writings on the court, civility, moral philosophy, political theory, and in the visual arts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aInterpersonal communicationzEuropexHistory. 0aInterpersonal communicationzItalyxHistory. 0aSecrecyxSocial aspectszEuropexHistory. 0aSecrecyxSocial aspectszItalyxHistory. 0aTruthfulness and falsehoodxSocial aspectszEuropexHistory. 0aTruthfulness and falsehoodxSocial aspectszItalyxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  a16th century.  a17th century.  aaffairs.  aaristocracy.  acanonical writing.  acommoners.  acommunication.  acontroversy.  acourt writings.  aculture of secrecy.  adisguise.  adishonesty.  adissimulation.  aearly modern europe.  aeurope.  ainner lives.  aitaly.  amasking emotions.  amodern history.  amoral philosophy.  anaples.  anetherlands.  aphilosophers.  apolitical silence.  apolitical theory.  aprivate lives.  arene descartes.  asecrecy.  asecret thoughts.  atextbooks.  atreatises.  avisual arts.  awriters and intellectuals.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094444240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520944442423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520944442/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles